column5:
Release custom headers for requests

This change removes the "experimental" gate to allow the client
to specify custom headers to send with requests.

The headers may be set globally using the `request-headers` config:
```js
spf.init({
  'request-headers': {
    'X-Custom-Header-One': 'Custom Value One',
    'X-Custom-Header-Two': 'Custom Value Two'
  }
})
```
Or, they may be set on a per-request basis for API calls using
the `headers` option:
```js
spf.navigate(url, {
  headers: {
    'X-Custom-Header-One': 'Custom Value One',
    'X-Custom-Header-Two': 'Custom Value Two'
  }
})
```

Closes #390

Allow custom headers to be sent with requests

In addition to the standard SPF headers (e.g. `X-SPF-Referer`), this change
allows the client to specify custom headers to send with requests.

These headers will be set globally using the `request-headers` config:
```js
spf.init({
  'request-headers': {
    'X-Custom-Header-One': 'Custom Value One',
    'X-Custom-Header-Two': 'Custom Value Two'
  }
})
```
Or, they may be set on a per-request basis for API calls using options:
```js
spf.navigate(url, {
  headers: {
    'X-Custom-Header-One': 'Custom Value One',
    'X-Custom-Header-Two': 'Custom Value Two'
  }
})
```

For now, gate the feature using the `experimental-request-headers` config
and the `experimental_headers` option.

Progress on #390

SPF: Support declarative dependency management in the beta script loader.

This is the third level of support for asynchronous script loading.  It
provides "declare" and "require" functions for lazy-loading scripts if
they are not "ready" using the following pattern:

Bootloader with Dependencies

    <script>
      spf.script.declare({
        // no dependencies
        'spf':  null,
        // one-to-one dependencies
        'base': 'spf',
        // many-to-one dependencies
        'common': 'base',
        'player': 'base',
        // one-to-many dependencies
        'watch': ['common', 'player'],
        ...
      });
      spf.script.require('watch', function() {
        // do something
      });
    </script>

For the bootloader API, "declare" and "require" are supported.
For the main API, "unrequire" is supported as well.

